The '''Sir Robert Rede's Lecturer''' is an annual appointment to give a public lecture, the '''Sir Robert Rede's Lecture''' (usually '''Rede Lecture''') at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>See [http://janus.lib.cam.ac.uk/db/node.xsp?id=Glossary%2FRede%20Lectures]. The series was put on its current footing in 1858.</ref> It is named for [[Robert Rede|Sir Robert Rede]], who was [[Chief Justice of the Common Pleas]] in the sixteenth century.
==Initial series== The initial series of lectures ranges from around 1668 to around 1856. In principle, there were three lectureships each year, on Logic, Philosophy and Rhetoric. These differed from the later individual lectures, in that they were appointments to a lectureship for a period of time, rather than an appointment for a one-off annual lecture. There was also a Mathematics lectureship which dated from an earlier time, while another term used was "Barnaby Lecturer", as the lecturers were elected on [[St Barnabas Day]]. A selection of the lecturers, who tended to have studied at Cambridge and be appointed after becoming Fellows of a College, is given below, with a full listing given in the sources.
===Mathematics Lecturers=== {{div col|colwidth=24em}} *1550 [[James Pilkington (bishop)|James Pilkington]] *1593 [[William Alabaster]] *1641 [[Ralph Cudworth]] *1643 [[Nathaniel Culverwell]] {{div col end}}
===Barnaby Lecturers=== {{div col|colwidth=24em}} *1776 Thomas Starkie the Elder (Mathematics)<ref>Father of [[Thomas Starkie]].</ref> *1738 [[Charles Moss (mathematician)|Charles Moss]] (Mathematics) *1746 [[John Berridge]] (Mathematics) *1755 [[John Michell]] (Mathematics) *1758 [[Thomas Postlethwaite]] (Mathematics) *1763 [[John Jebb (1736–1786)|John Jebb]] (Mathematics) *1765 [[Richard Watson (bishop)|Richard Watson]] (Mathematics) *1770 [[William Paley]] (Mathematics) *1783 [[William Farish (professor)|William Farish]] (Mathematics) *1789 [[Francis John Hyde Wollaston]] (Mathematics) *1807 [[Robert Woodhouse]] (Mathematics) *1831 [[John Stevens Henslow]] (Mathematics) *1842 [[David Thomas Ansted]] (Mathematics) *1846 [[George Gabriel Stokes]] (Mathematics) *1851 [[Henry Richards Luard]] (Mathematics) *1855 [[Richard Shilleto]] (Mathematics) {{div col end}}
===Rede Lecturers=== {{div col|colwidth=24em}} *1706 [[John Addenbrooke (philanthropist)|John Addenbrooke]] (Logic) *1717 [[John Addenbrooke (philanthropist)|John Addenbrooke]] (Logic) *1723 [[John Jortin]] (Rhetoric) *1730 [[Edmund Law]] (Rhetoric) *1740 [[Thomas Pyle]] (Rhetoric) *1763 [[Richard Watson (bishop)|Richard Watson]] (Philosophy) *1764 [[John Jebb (1736–1786)|John Jebb]] (Rhetoric) *1781 [[George Pretyman]] (Philosophy) *1783 [[Isaac Milner]] (Philosophy) *1785 [[William Farish (professor)|William Farish]] (Logic) *1785 [[Joseph Dacre Carlyle]] (Rhetoric) *1794 [[Bewick Bridge]] (Logic) *1796 [[Bewick Bridge]] (Logic) *1798 [[George Butler (headmaster)|George Butler]] (Logic) *1803 [[Bewick Bridge]] (Rhetoric) *1805 [[Ralph Tatham]] (Philosophy) *1806 [[George Cecil Renouard]] (Philosophy) *1809 [[Henry Bickersteth]] (Logic) *1812 [[John Kaye (English bishop)|John Kaye]] (Logic) *1819 [[George Peacock]] (Philosophy) *1822 [[Connop Thirlwall]] (Logic) *1825 [[John Stevens Henslow]] (Philosophy) *1828 [[Joshua King]] (Rhetoric) *1837 [[Edward Harold Browne]] (Philosophy) *1838 [[Samuel Earnshaw]] (Philosophy) *1843 [[John William Colenso]] (Philosophy) *1844 [[Joseph Woolley]] (Rhetoric) *1846 [[Hugh Andrew Johnstone Munro]] (Philosophy) *1850 [[Charles Anthony Swainson]] (Logic) *1851 [[John James Stewart Perowne]] (Philosophy) *1853 [[John Couch Adams]] (Philosophy) *1853 [[John James Stewart Perowne]] (Rhetoric) {{div col end}}
==New series== From 1858, the lecture was re-established as a one-off annual lecture, delivered by a person appointed by the Vice-Chancellor of the university. The names of the appointees and the titles of their lectures are given below.
